'''Geoffrey Charles Smith''', [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] (born 1953) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[mathematician]]. He is Senior Lecturer in Mathematics at the [[University of Bath]] (where he works in [[group theory]]) and current professor in residence at [[Wells Cathedral School]].

He was educated at [[Trinity School of John Whitgift|Trinity School]] in [[Croydon]], and attended [[Keble College, Oxford]], the [[University of Warwick]], and the [[University of Manchester]], where he gained a [[Ph.D.]] in 1983.<ref>{{MathGenealogy |id=104634}}</ref> His thesis, ''Zeta functions of torsion-free finitely generated nilpotent groups'', was written under the direction of [[Dan Segal]].

Smith was the leader of the [[United Kingdom]] team at the [[International Mathematical Olympiad]] between 2002 and 2010, a longer continuous period than any other person.<ref name="report2010">{{cite web|url=http://www.imo-register.org.uk/2010-report.pdf|title=International Mathematical Olympiad 2010 UK leader's report}}</ref> Under his leadership, the team achieved an average of 20th place, stronger than under the preceding [[Imre Leader|leader]] (1999 to 2001, 24th), but weaker than in the previous period of two alternating leaders (1991 to 1998, 11th/12th).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.imo-official.org/country_team_r.aspx?code=UNK|title=International Mathematical Olympiad}}</ref> He returned to the position as the leader of the British Mathematical Olympiad from 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imo-official.org/year_reg_team.aspx?year=2013&code=UNK|title=International Mathematical Olympiad United Kingdom participants 2013}}</ref> Between 2013 and 2018 the team achieved an average of 13/14th place including three top 10 finishes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.imo-official.org/country_team_r.aspx?code=UNK|title=International Mathematical Olympiad}}</ref>

Smith oversaw a quantitative increase in training: annual events in [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]] (moving to [[The Queen's College, Oxford]] from 2009), at [[Oundle School]], in [[Hungary]], at [[Trinity College, Cambridge]], and immediately prior to the IMO itself.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bmoc.maths.org/home/trinity.shtml|title=IMO Squad Training Camps}}</ref> He also thrice won the IMO Golden Microphone, awarded to the national team leader who makes the most speeches to the IMO Jury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imo-register.org.uk/golden-microphone.html|title=International Mathematical Olympiad Golden Microphone}}</ref> In 2010 he was elected to the IMO Advisory Board<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imo-official.org/advisory.aspx?year=2011|title=IMO Advisory Board 2011}}</ref> for a four-year period.<ref name="report2010" /> Smith was elected as the chair of the International Mathematical Olympiad for the term of 2014-2018<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bath.ac.uk/news/2014/07/08/international-maths-olympiad/|title=IMO Chair 2014-2018}}</ref> and was re-elected in 2018. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imo-official.org/advisory.aspx?year=2019|title=IMO Chair 2018-2022}}</ref>

Smith also prepared UK teams for the [[Romanian Masters in Mathematics]] tournament (which they won in 2008), and for participation as guests at the annual [[Balkan Mathematical Olympiad]].

As well as group theory, he is also interested in [[Euclidean geometry]]. He often collaborates with [[Christopher Bradley (mathematician)|Christopher Bradley]] and [[David Monk (mathematician)|David Monk]], and has published several papers on Forum Geometricorum, the online geometry journal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forumgeom.fau.edu/|title=Forum Geometricorum}}</ref>

In June 2011 Smith was awarded an [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] for services to education following his contributions toward organising [[Royal Institution]] Maths Masterclasses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bath.ac.uk/news/2011/06/12/geoff-smith-mbe/|title=Dr Geoff Smith awarded MBE in Queen’s Birthday Honours}}</ref>

