'''Peter Ludwig Mejdell Sylow''' ({{IPA-all| ˈsyːlɔv}}) (12 December 1832 – 7 September 1918) was a [[Norway|Norwegian]] [[mathematician]] who proved foundational results in [[group theory]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Birkeland |first=Bent |title=Ludvig Sylow |publisher=Norsk biografisk leksikon |url=https://nbl.snl.no/Ludvig_Sylow |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref>
==Biography==
He was born and died in [[Oslo|Christiania]] (now [[Oslo]]). Sylow was a son of government minister [[Thomas Edvard von Westen Sylow]], and a brother of military officer and sports official [[Carl Sylow]]. He attended [[Oslo Cathedral School|Christiania Cathedral School]] (1850) and the [[University of Oslo|University of Christiania]] (cand.real.  1856) .<ref name=heh-1912>{{cite encyclopedia |year=1912 |title=Sylow, Peter Ludwig Mejdell |encyclopedia=[[Hvem er Hvem?]] Haandbog over samtidige norske mænd og kvinder |edition=1 |language=Norwegian |editor1-last=Brinchmann |editor1-first=Christopher |editor1-link=Christopher Brinchmann |editor2-last=Daae |editor2-first=Anders |editor3-last=Hammer |editor3-first=K. V. |publisher=Aschehoug |location=Kristiania |url=http://runeberg.org/hvemerhvem/1912/0266.html |accessdate=8 October 2016}}</ref>

Sylow was a high school teacher at [[Hartvig Nissen School]], later before becoming a headmaster in [[Halden]] from 1858 to 1898. He was  a substitute lecturer at [[University of Christiania]] in 1862, covering [[Galois theory]]. It was then that he posed the question that led to his theorems regarding [[Sylow subgroup]]s. Sylow published the [[Sylow theorems]] in 1872, and subsequently devoted eight years of his life, with [[Sophus Lie]], to the project of editing the mathematical works of his countryman, [[Niels Henrik Abel]]. In 1898, he was appointed professor at the University of Christiania.<ref>{{cite web |last1=O'Connor |first1=J. J.  |last2=Robertson |first2=E. F. |title=Peter Ludwig Mejdell Sylow |publisher=School of Mathematics and Statistics. University of St Andrews, Scotland |url=http://www-history.mcs.st-and.ac.uk/Biographies/Sylow.html |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Birkeland |first=Bent |title=Ludvig Sylow |publisher=Norsk biografisk leksikon |url=https://nbl.snl.no/Ludvig_Sylow |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref>

In 1853, he was awarded the Crown Prince's gold medal  (''Kronprinsens gullmedalje'') by the [[University of Oslo]]. In 1894 he was awarded an honorary doctorate from the [[University of Copenhagen]]. <ref>{{cite web
|url =   http://www.muv.uio.no/uios-historie/epoker/1811-1870/kronprinsen-kvist-010907.html|title= Student Peter Ludvig Meydell Sylow
|publisher=   University of Oslo|accessdate= February 1, 2018}}</ref>

